	<main>
		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="community archaeology group on Lasqueti Island" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-community-archaeology-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Community archaeology has become a way to reconcile the past between those who have called a land- and seascape home for millennia and those who are newcomers. One project on Xwe’etay, or Lasqueti Island, British Columbia, is a signpost for the future. Photo by Grant Callegari</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Neighborhood Digs</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">On the Pacific Northwest coast—and around the world—community archaeology is helping people reconcile with each other and their history.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						Text by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/brian-payton/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Brian Payton</a>								<br/>
							Photos by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/grant-callegari/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Grant Callegari</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
